> Do you have suggestions of academic papers that discuss ethics in day-to-day research (as distinct from IRB approval)?
**assistant**:
> Certainly! There are numerous academic papers that discuss ethics in day-to-day research beyond the scope of Institutional Review Board (IRB) approval. These papers often address issues such as data management, authorship, peer review, conflicts of interest, and research integrity. Here are a few notable papers that you might find useful:
> 
> 1. Shamoo, A. E., & Resnik, D. B. (2009). Responsible Conduct of Research (2nd ed.). Oxford University Press.
>    This comprehensive book covers a wide range of ethical issues in day-to-day research, providing guidance for researchers, students, and administrators.
> 
> 2. Macrina, F. L. (2014). Scientific Integrity: Text and Cases in Responsible Conduct of Research (4th ed.). ASM Press.
>    This book covers various aspects of research ethics, with a focus on case studies that illustrate real-world dilemmas researchers may face in their day-to-day work.
> 
> 3. Fanelli, D. (2009). How Many Scientists Fabricate and Falsify Research? A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis of Survey Data. PLoS ONE, 4(5), e5738.
>    This paper reviews survey data to estimate the prevalence of fabrication, falsification, and other forms of misconduct in scientific research, offering insights into the importance of ethical conduct in everyday research.
> 
> 4. Resnik, D. B., & Master, Z. (2013). Policies to Promote Research Integrity: A Systematic Review. Accountability in Research, 20(3), 175-196.
>    This paper systematically reviews policies designed to promote research integrity and discusses their effectiveness in maintaining ethical conduct in day-to-day research.
> 
> 5. Anderson, M. S., Ronning, E. A., De Vries, R., & Martinson, B. C. (2007). The Perverse Effects of Competition on Scientists' Work and Relationships. Science and Engineering Ethics, 13(4), 437-461.
>    This paper examines how competitive pressures in the research environment can lead to unethical behavior in day-to-day research, such as data manipulation and withholding of results.
> 
> 6. Wicherts, J. M., Borsboom, D., Kats, J., & Molenaar, D. (2006). The Poor Availability of Psychological Research Data for Reanalysis. American Psychologist, 61(7), 726-728.
>    This paper highlights the importance of data sharing and transparency in psychological research, arguing that these practices are crucial for maintaining ethical standards in day-to-day research.
> 
> 7. Tennant, J. P., Dugan, J. M., Graziotin, D., Jacques, D. C., Waldner, F., Mietchen, D., ... & Çöltekin, A. (2017). A Multi-Disciplinary Perspective on Emergent and Future Innovations in Peer Review. F1000Research, 6, 1151.
>    This paper discusses the role of peer review in promoting ethical conduct in research and explores potential innovations that could improve the process, such as open peer review and post-publication review.
> 
> These papers should provide a solid starting point for understanding the various ethical issues that can arise in day-to-day research and the importance of addressing them.
